  urldate = {2023-03-02},
  abstract = {When President Bill Clinton stood on the south rim of the Grand Canyon and created Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument in September 1996, after informing Utah's congressional delegation and governor only twenty-four hours earlier, local and state reaction to the announcement nearly reached a breaking point. Certainly aware that some people in the local communities would not be pleased with the designation, the president could not fully have anticipated the maelstrom that followed and the controversy that the establishment of the monument continues to provoke. State officials and local residents of the sleepy communities in southern Utah balked at the move,},
