  doi = {10.2307/j.ctvwrm3ww.17},
  urldate = {2023-03-02},
  abstract = {Policies for conservation of nature also changed profoundly during the modern environmental policy era. Throughout most of their history the national forests were managed for multiple uses: in practice, primarily for timber production as a priority, plus grazing, wildlife, recreation, mining, and others. A few distinctive places were set aside as national parks and wildlife refuges. Most other public lands---most of them in the western states---were either allotted for cattle grazing, leased for coal or oil and gas extraction, or simply left open for mining claims, off-road vehicle use, and public entry. Conservation on private lands was left},
